" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="860336"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018577-20180323-194546"/></CodeI><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gfod"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gwbs"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gwbs"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Wine/Beer/Spirits</CodeD><CodeI org="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="837821"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018577-20180323-194546"/><CodeA name="rule" value="857425"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="3"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">I/BVG I/DST I/RES I/RLO M/LEAH M/NCY N/FCG N/GEN N/LIF R/NME R/US </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday BEST NEW BEERS BEST SOUR BEER BEST SPRING BEERS BLACK IPA DARK BEERS LIGHTER DARK BEERS SB103852872163798845487045841054133561889561 Grinkey, Jeremy Jeffries, Ron Melis, Chad SYND CODES_REVIEWED Half Full </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OLEM OLFD </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Life</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Come Over to the Dark (Beer) Side; A darker brew isn't always a wintry gut-buster. From clean and bracing to sweet and smooth, these aren't the beers you think they are</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>IF CRAFT BEER teaches us anything, it's that <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canned-beer-for-beer-snobs-the-6-best-craft-brews-to-crack-1493828707">looks</ELink> can be deceiving. Serious brews have the silliest names; <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-craft-beer-explosion-how-to-find-the-brews-for-you-1517509748">corner dives offer rare brews on tap</ELink>. And dark beers, presumed to be bearers of barrel-aged heft and boozy potency, now beguile with unexpected flavors. Dark can be tart, smooth, hoppy, fruited and even, yes, light.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Beer gets its color from grain; blacker brews start with roasted malts, dried over higher heat than the pale malts used in Pilsners and IPAs. Dark grains may be cooked hot and fast like coffee beans, toasted low and long, or smoked over beech or alder. They lend more than pigment: Tastes of caramelized and charred sugars translate to the glass. Used with abandon, dark grains are bitter bruisers, but nuances lurk in the darkness—complex flavors akin to those in some single-origin chocolates.</Para><Para>Still, a darker pour often triggers memories of unctuous Guinness or big, strapping barrel-aged stouts. "I see it all the time at beer festivals, when people ask for the lightest beer we have," said Chad Melis of Colorado's Oskar Blues Brewery. Old Chub, a Scotch ale, is smooth, slightly sweet and ideal for a brisk spring day—but looks dark as a midwinter night. When it comes to opening people's eyes to a beer like this, Mr. Melis wishes he had a blindfold.</Para><Para>Dark grains can also marry nicely with expressive additions like fruit, spice, <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ipas-for-people-who-don8217t-like-ipas-1390576694">juicy new-world hops</ELink> and <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444860104577559203710998954">sour bacteria</ELink> that might overpower lighter malts. In black IPAs such as 21st Amendment Brewery's Back in Black, fruity hops take on the chocolate-cherry bitter-brightness of light-roast espresso. The sharp acidity of wild yeasts and lactic bacteria can make beers without backbone biting and sharp, but the rich notes of dark grain provide balancing depth.</Para><Para>Brewers know well that styles aren't sacrosanct. Rustic-born brews like wild-fermented sours probably began their history dark, made with roughly dried grains long before industrial malting allowed for a lighter touch. Ron Jeffries of Jolly Pumpkin Artisan Ales in Dexter, Mich., tapped into that history with Bam Noire, a zippy, slightly sour—and dark—saison. "There were villagers outside the brewery with torches, saying, Saisons aren't supposed to be dark! A dark farmhouse ale, what's that?" he said. "There's definitely a learning curve."</Para><Para>It's worth getting past the cognitive dissonance to appreciate the Bruery's Tart of Darkness, an oak-aged stout infused with funky wild yeasts, on its own terms. "The aroma [suggests] those roasty flavors you expect," said Jeremy Grinkey, head of the Bruery's sour program, Bruery Terreux. "But you taste a clean acidity, and the body's thinned out by that acid. It's a really unique experience."</Para><Para>1. Boulevard Flora Obscura (5.8% ABV) Hopped-up with bright, fruity strains like Mosaic and Galaxy, this beer is orange-sorbet sweet with a coffee chaser.</Para><Para>2. MadTree Identity Crisis (6.9% ABV) Roasted barley meets zippy lemon rind and grapefruit in this snappy spin on a bone-dry porter.</Para><Para>3. Jolly Pumpkin Bam Noire (4.5% ABV) A dark saison soured in oak barrels. Chocolate-cherry-truffle richness meets tongue tingling fizz and earthy smoke.</Para><Para>4. The Bruery Tart of Darkness (6.6% ABV) On the nose, rich chocolate and the sweet vanilla swirl of oak; on the tongue, puckering plums. A truly trippy brew.</Para><Para>5. Firestone Walker Nitro Merlin (5.5% ABV) With a nitrogen-infused pour and a dose of lactose sugar, this oatmeal stout, now sold in cans, is creamy as a latte.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By William Bostwick </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/come-over-to-the-dark-beer-side-1521812735" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

